DOCUMENT();       

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl"
           );
       
TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.


$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$m = random(7,12,0.5);
$b = random(-1400,-1050,50);
$x0 = random(1310,1340,2);
$y0 = $m*$x0+$b;
$dx = random(150,250,10);

$dy = $m*$dx;
$y0_th = round($y0/1000);
$y0_hund = $y0 - $y0_th*1000;
if ($y0 - $y0_th*1000 >=0) { $y0_hund = $y0 - $y0_th*1000 }
   else { $y0_th = $y0_th -1; $y0_hund = $y0 - $y0_th*1000};

$x1 = $x0+$dx;
$y1 = $y0+$dy;
$y1_th = round($y1/1000);
if ($y1 - $y1_th*1000 >=0) { $y1_hund = $y1 - $y1_th*1000 }
   else { $y1_th = $y1_th -1; $y1_hund = $y1 - $y1_th*1000};

$k = -$b/$m;
$s = 1/$m;

$ans1 = "$m x + $b";
$ans2 = "$s y + $k";

$x3 = $x1 + random(350,550,10);
$y3 = $m*$x3 + $b;
$y3_th = round($y3/1000);
if ($y3 - $y3_th*1000 >=0) { $y3_hund = $y3 - $y3_th*1000 }
   else { $y3_th = $y3_th -1; $y3_hund = $y3 - $y3_th*1000};



BEGIN_TEXT
Question 40:
$BR $SPACE $BR
A theater manager graphed weekly profits as a function of the number of patrons and found that the relationship was linear.  One week profit was ${DOLLAR}$y0_th,$y0_hund when $x0 patrons attended.  Another week $x1 patrons produced a profit of ${DOLLAR}$y1_th,$y1_hund.
$BR
$HR
$BR

a) Find a formula for weekly profit, $BITALIC y ${EITALIC}, as a function of the number of patrons, $BITALIC x ${EITALIC}.  Do not enter any commas in your formula.
$BR
\( y = \ \) \{ ans_rule(30) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) How much will profits increase if 1 more patron goes to the theater? $SPACE $SPACE   ${DOLLAR}\{ ans_rule(15) \} (no comma in your answer)
$BR $SPACE $BR
c) What is the break-even point (the number of patrons for which there is zero profit)?  \{ ans_rule(10) \} patrons (no comma in your answer)
$BR $SPACE $BR
d) Find a formula for the number of patrons as a function of the profit.  Do not enter any commas in your formula.
$BR
\( x = \ \) \{ ans_rule(30) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
f) If the weekly profit was ${DOLLAR}$y3_th,$y3_hund, how many patrons attended the theater? $SPACE $SPACE  \{ ans_rule(10) \} patrons (no comma in your answer)
END_TEXT

ANS(fun_cmp($ans1,vars=>'x'));
ANS(num_cmp($m));
ANS(num_cmp($k));
ANS(fun_cmp($ans2,vars=>'y'));
ANS(fun_cmp($x3));

$disp_b = -$b;

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR
$BBOLD SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR
a) We are given two points on the line, ($x0, $y0) and ($x1, $y1).  We can compute the slope
$BR
\[ m = \frac{\triangle y}{\triangle x} = \frac{$y1 - $y0}{$x1 - $x0} = $m \]
$BR
Then we use the point ($x0, $y0) to solve for the $BITALIC y${EITALIC}-intercept $BITALIC b $EITALIC, \( $y0 = $m ($x0) + b \) so \( b = $b \).  The equation is therefore \( y = $m x + $b \) .
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) This is the slope of the line, ${DOLLAR}$m per patron.
$BR $SPACE $BR
c) To find the break-even point, we find the number of patrons, $BITALIC x${EITALIC}, that makes the profit $BITALIC y,${EITALIC} equal to 0, i.e. we set $BITALIC y $EITALIC equal to zero and solve for $BITALIC x${EITALIC}.
$BR $SPACE $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( 0 = $b + $m x \) 
$BR $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( $disp_b = $m x \)
$BR $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( x = $k \ \mbox{patrons} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
d) Rewriting our expression in (a):
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( y = $m x + $b \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( $m x = y - $b \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( x = \frac{y - $b}{$m} = \frac{y}{$m} - \frac{$b}{$m} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
e) If the profit was ${DOLLAR}${DOLLAR}$y3_th,$y3_hund, the number of patrons would be
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( x = \frac{$y3}{$m} - \frac{$b}{$m} = $x3 \ \mbox{patrons} \)
$BR
END_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();   # This should be the last executable line in the problem.